text: Okay, do you know of any male APNs in the workforce? Yes, I know of, um, how many? I think one, two. Two? Yes. So, sounds like very few right? Yes. Okay, maybe share a bit about your practice setting that causes you to only be able to nurse male patients. I think that my patient setting is in the paediatric setting. So, when considering a male nurse to be an APN, one has to consider or track record whether there were patients who complained because we were not sensitive to their gender and whether the male nurse can actually adapt to whichever area they are in and practice with protecting the patient's dignity at all times. So, it seems like all these were said explicitly to you? You mean in terms of the... I think thankfully with very good nurse managers who were able to advocate for me, they were able to convince the APNs that I would be a suitable candidate because of the way I practiced in the emergency department. So, you heard of all these things from? In terms of? How do you know that they will do a check on your feedback from patients, whether you are gender sensitive? How do you get to know all this information? This is information that the APNs were telling me in terms of their selection criteria and who they select to go for the interviews because they have to gather feedback from the... So, it's not just for males? No, not just for males. But I think that when they were considering putting me into the inpatient ward, these were also some of the factors that they were considering. Whether or not I'm able to function in the inpatient ward, especially being the first male to be posted there, were some of the considerations based on my previous practice. So, I think that when selecting a male nurse to be an APN, these are also certain things that they will have to scrutinise and consider before recommending me to go for a future male nurse to go for the APN programme. So, before you, there were no other male nurses in the inpatient setting? Not in my institution, but in another institution, yes, there were male nurses in the pediatric ward. Yes, there are two more right now. One in the high dependency and the other in the surgical ward. I was bonded because of my degree programme in NUS. And when I selected my preference to my institution, they had to brief me and warn me that, you know, these are the limitations of your practice when you come in. And because of, I think, a few years of advocacy and from our managers pushing, they realised that they should consider otherwise and that's why they put me there. Okay, that's very interesting history and it continues on. So, do you think that, okay, I think we covered this but I just want to be clearer about your perspective towards this. Do you think that nursing leaders take into consideration the gender of the RN when nominating him or her for the MN programme? Definitely. I think that male nurses generally stand out in the institution. So, that's one factor and then when you have already an outstanding person there because of the gender, then you get more scrutiny on the person's ability and capabilities. So, there will be more thought in process done in terms of considering the selection of male APN. From my experience, I've just been very blessed to have very good bosses who recognise my strengths and my limitations. How that I was very outspoken in trying to advocate for better care and also trying to think of ideas within the institution that can be changed to improve processes and improve safety. So, that gender bias is something that is very real and I'm fully aware of it when I'm in the hospital. So, it's how you use it to your advantage to help to make the institution better. I said it's a double-edged sword because on the contrary, you can be very outspoken but at the same time, your colleagues don't like you. So, you spoke about gender bias and how when the same thing is being spoken by a male and a female, when a male does it, it seems more accepting and louder and weightier. In the context of the corporate world or any other kind of workforce where there is somewhat a bit more males, there's a good diversity. Why then do you think that this phenomenon of gender bias towards males is still present? I think it's just a social norm. I really cannot explain it. I really think it's just a social norm that has been integrated in us. I mean, yeah. Okay, so if we expand this question, because we are just talking about NM programme selection, but let's say we are looking at in general for professional development of RNs. Do you think that gender biases are present? Not pernading to just APN practise, but for professional development of RNs across all career tracks, across all settings, do you think that there is gender bias? Yes, I think there is gender bias. Usually, they will be more inclined to want to put a male to be of a manager role. This is what I observed in, like among the other male nurses that I know of in the hospital. So the career progression will be smoother, so long as they don't cause a kerfuffle at work. And yeah, the recognition that possibly, like there is a stereotype that males have better management style because they are more task oriented and less emotional in their decision making makes male nurses better nurse managers. So even that has a gender bias when selecting nurse managers. So this is the managerial role, right? But what about the clinical role and education role? I don't know. I don't know whether there is a bias towards that. But I know that specifically the management role is quite biased towards male nurses. Okay, so it's actually for their benefit, right? Yes. So what you're trying to say is that males do have a higher chance of progressing further than females in nursing. Yes. So then it goes back to my question. Why is there still so few males in the APN workforce? Is it they choose not to? Or are they not being identified? Are there other existing barriers that is deterring men from joining the workforce? I think that it is just a transposition of the general sentiment, in my opinion. So, very few RNs, whether male or female, want to do the APN program in order to advance their career. Interestingly enough, in my institution, the ones who want to do the APN program are graduates from the undergraduate program from SIT and NUS. So people who have advanced placement when they started working and are more inclined to progress their careers and to develop themselves further. So, in my opinion, the limited number of male RNs could be also attributed to the limited number of male NUS and SIT graduates in this respect. So, I mean, even though there is 11% of the workforce are male nurses, however, maybe we can dig deeper. How many percent of these 11% are actually graduates from SIT and NUS who have a higher inclination towards advancing their career? Because this was their first degree, this was their first professional certification and they would be keen to advance it to a second level or a third level assuming they have done their advanced diploma. That's a very good point that you raised. But if we were to compare with the diploma graduates, that would also be their first professional sort of certification, right? Why then do you think that the SIT and NUS graduates are more inclined to pursue the track more than the diploma grads? I mean, sorry, let me just rephrase. So I feel that the limited number of male APMs, also it's an extrapolation of these barriers which are very general and they are not gender specific. Then do you think it's important to have more males in the APM workforce? I think it's important. It's important because it allows the practice to be expanded further. It allows more emphasis because we are outstanding as males in the first place. And in the workforce, if we are male APMs, it makes it even more outstanding. It allows us to also push APMs towards more leadership roles in order to change policy and to advance the APM profession further. So like I mentioned just now about the gender bias towards males being into leadership roles like the management roles. Similarly, I think within the APM program, if you have more maleness, it's likely that the APMs will want to develop these APMs to become APM leaders in their institution. In order to carry out, make changes and push for more integration into the healthcare practice. I think male nurses generally are good collaborators. They develop good rapport with the physicians, male and female doctors. They are able to have good rapport also because of people's impression of them. I think that male nurses are outstanding and generally good in their practice. So when you have that coupled with a qualified APM, I think that synergises and puts you in a good place to help to push the APM program further in collaborating in more areas of services. Why then do you think that females fare a bit poorer in all these aspects? I think it goes back down to the gender bias that males tend to be more task-oriented in their decision-making and less emotionally-oriented in their decision-making. So they tend to be less immune to the office politics and the office politics. With so many feminist movements happening now, you would think that people are more cognisant of gender stereotypes. Why is it that whatever you are observing in a clinical setting still hosts so much stereotypes? I think the polarity is also because of the fact that we are a minority. It is analogous to the impression of how female national service regulars are more capable and very outstanding in their role. How do you think we can get more paediatrics male APNs in? I think identifying them early on, and helping to flag up their interests. I think that will be an important way. That's also one of the reasons why very few male nurses want to go into paediatrics. So I think that we have a good amount of acceptance wherever we go, especially to the younger colleagues. Because I think the older colleagues have a very strong mindset. Males shouldn't be doing this job, and why are they doing this job? But I think now, with the new generation coming, and the mindset not being of a very stereotypical mindset, I think that it will become more accepting. I think that there's a female-male rivalry going on in the inpatient ward. You spoke about gender diversity, can you please share a bit more about the benefits of having gender diversity in nursing? In particular, APM practice. In particular, APM practice? Well, you can start vague first, you can start from just as a whole in nursing practice. Why would it be good to have a more equally distributed gender? I think it makes the APM program less skewed towards involving emotions in terms of the decisions to collaboration. So an example of this is how my collaborating physician, who recommended me for the program, was telling me about having difficulty convincing the leadership that we need an APM within the department. But I think having a male APM would allow the leadership to see that, no actually I'm not making sense. I think in terms of education, it is something that is outstanding. So an example is that one of my family friends, one of the eldest in my family friends was a male tutor in school of nursing. So his name, I cannot say his name, sorry. But a lot of our first generation nursing leaders who went to school of nursing remember him because of the way he teaches and how he was one of the very few male nurses who were tutors in the school of nursing. Actually there were only two of them, according to some of them. And how he was very gentle and very outstanding because of his gender and also because of the way he teaches. So I think that when we talk about the APM as good clinical leaders and playing a role in the clinical education for registered nurses, I think having males there is an advantage because, first they are outstanding and secondly I think that when you're placed in a position where you are conducting education, people listen to you more and that allows us to be better teachers, better clinical teachers on the ground for the registered nurses. I talked about the leadership and how male nurses might have advantage as well. But I don't really see how our practice actually clinically differs because I think that the way we carry out our clinical tasks are the same. The amount, the level of care we give is the same. Perhaps, especially the elderly in the public might be more receptive to a male APM. I think generally it's tapping again on the gender bias and how male care providers have a better reception to care by the elderly because people listen to us more. So they assume that we're probably like doctors or something. And that happens all the time. In fact, that happens in the emergency when I was practicing as a male RN, when I was doing triage and very often the grandparents are the ones who bring the child in and they will assume that I'm a doctor because I'm a male. So similarly, I think that we will not struggle so much with the acceptance of our care in the clinical practice because of our gender and because of the public's assumption that we are physicians when we are not. That's a very good point. I never saw it that way. So generally it can really help to elevate the professional image of APMs, right? Yes. I have covered all my questions but before I end, do you have anything to add towards this topic, towards anything you missed out sharing? I think I covered most of it. Yes, I think so too. Okay, thank you. Anything else to say? No, I'm all ears. Let me stop the recording.
